Q4. Build various exponential smoothing models on the training data and evaluate the model using RMSE on the test data. Other models such as regression,naïve forecast models and simple average models. should also be built on the training data and check the performance on the test data using RMSE. ¶

1. Naive Model ¶

$\hat{y}_{t+1} = y_t$

In Naive Model, the prediction for tomorrow is the same as today and the prediction for day after tomorrow is tomorrow and since the prediction of tomorrow is same as today,therefore the prediction for day after tomorrow is same as today.¶

In [18]:
# Training the model on sparkling_train dataset to predict the last value as the future value.

NaiveModel_Train = sparkling_train.copy()
NaiveModel_Test = sparkling_test.copy()

NaiveModel_Test['Naive'] = np.asarray(sparkling_train['Sparkling'])[len(np.asarray(sparkling_train['Sparkling']))-1]

# Plot the train and test data into forecast.

plt.plot(NaiveModel_Train['Sparkling'], label='Sparkling Train')
plt.plot(sparkling_test['Sparkling'], label='Sparkling Test')

plt.plot(NaiveModel_Test['Naive'], label='Naive Forecast on Test Data')

plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.title("Naive Forecast")
plt.grid();
In [19]:
# Calculating the error for the Vaive Forecast.

Naive_Model_Error = metrics.mean_squared_error(sparkling_test['Sparkling'],NaiveModel_Test['Naive'],squared=False)
print("For Naive Bayees forecast on the Test Data, RMSE is : %3.3f" %(Naive_Model_Error))

For Naive Bayees forecast on the Test Data, RMSE is : 3864.279

Inference (Naive Model)¶

Naive Model assumes the last value of the training dataset to be applicable, for all the test dataset and hence is not a suitable method in time series forecasting which has Trend & Seasonality. The RMSE is also very high here (3865).

2. Linear Regression Model ¶

Linear Regression typically is not suitable for time series analysis. This model that assumes a linear relationship between the input variables (x) and the single output variable (y). More specifically, that y can be calculated from a linear combination of the input variables.¶

5. Exponential Smoothing Model ¶

Exponential smoothing averages or exponentially weighted moving averages consist of forecast based on previous periods data with exponentially declining influence on the older observations. Exponential smoothing methods consist of special case exponential moving with notation ETS (Error, Trend, Seasonality) where each can be none(N), additive (N), additive damped (Ad), Multiplicative (M) or multiplicative damped (Md).¶

SES - ETS(A, N, N) - Simple Exponential Smoothing¶

In Single ES, the forecast at time (t + 1) is given by Winters,1960

  • $F_{t+1} = \alpha Y_t + (1-\alpha) F_t$

Parameter $\alpha$ is called the smoothing constant and its value lies between 0 and 1. Since the model uses only one smoothing constant, it is called Single Exponential Smoothing.

DES - ETS(A, A, N) - Double Exponential Smoothing¶

  • Intercept or Level equation, $L_t$ is given by: $L_t = {\alpha}{Y_t} + (1 - \alpha)F_t$

  • Trend equation is given by $T_t = {\beta}{(L_t - L_{t-1})} + (1 - \beta)T_{t-1}$

Here, $\alpha$ and $\beta$ are the smoothing constants for level and trend, respectively,

  • 0 <$\alpha$ < 1 and 0 < $\beta$ < 1.

The forecast at time t + 1 is given by

  • $F_{t+1} = L_t + T_t$
  • $F_{t+n} = L_t + nT_t$

TES - ETS(A, A, A) - Triple Exponential Smoothing¶

In DES, we estimated the level and trend based on the optimum value of the smoothing parameters $\alpha \text{ & } \beta$. However, if there is any seasonality in the data, DES method will miss it since it neglects seasonality.

Triple Exponential Smoothing corrects for this by incorporating a seasonality component that again uses a dampening parameter $\gamma$ to incorporate seasonality variation over time.

a. Simple Exponential Smoothing - SES (Winter) ¶

# Training the model on sparkling_train dataset to predict the last value as the future value with SES Model.

SES_Train = sparkling_train.copy()
SES_Test = sparkling_test.copy()

Model_SES = SimpleExpSmoothing(SES_Train,initialization_method='estimated')
Model_SES_Autofit = Model_SES.fit(optimized=True)
SES_Predict = Model_SES_Autofit.forecast(steps=len(SES_Test))
print(Model_SES_Autofit.params)

# Plotting the Training data, Test data and the forecasted values.

plt.plot(SES_Train, label='Train')
plt.plot(SES_Test, label='Test')
plt.plot(SES_Predict, label='Alpha = 0.07 Simple Exponential Smoothing predictions on Test Set')
plt.legend(loc='best')
plt.grid()
plt.title('Simple Exponential Smoothing')

# Calculate and display the error (RMSE).

SES_Error = metrics.mean_squared_error(SES_Test.values,SES_Predict.values,squared=False)
print("For SES forecast on the Test Data,  RMSE is %3.3f" %(SES_Error))

Q7. Comment on the model thus built and report your findings and suggest the measures that the company should be taking for future sales. ¶

Model Forecasting Summary

Model Type RMSE Value Prediction Outcome
Naive Model 3864 Prediction values for all test datapoints is same as last value of training dataset.
Linear Regression Model 1389 Prediction based on the assumption that a linear relationship exists between time and sales.
Simple Average Model 1275 Prediction values for all test datapoints is equal to the average value of training dataset.
Moving Average Model (2, 4, 6, 8 Month) 3046, 2021, 1521, 1338 Prediction values for all test datapoints is equal to the average value of the training dataset (2, 4 6, 8 Month).
Simple Exponential Model 1338 Predicted values is based on an estimated level based on optimum value of the smoothing parameter 𝛼 (No Trend / Seasonality).
Double Exponential Model 5292 Predicted values is based on estimated level based on the optimum value of the smoothing parameter 𝛼 and also a trend component based on the value of Beta (No Seasonality).
Triple Exponential Model (Multiplicative/Additive) 402, 386, 380, 354 Predicted values is estimated level (baed on alpha), trend (based on beta), seasonality (based on gamma).

Triple Exponential Model - Insights / Summary

  1. Triple Exponential Model produces the best forecast as it takes into account all 3 componenets - Level, Trend, Seasonality while doing the prediction. This also results into least RMSE of ~ 380.

  2. This TES (Multiplicative-Additive) model built forecasts for next 12 months which would be quite accurate, keeping historical trend / seasonality in mind.

  3. The Wine Sale is expected to go up in the last quarter (Oct - Dec) and is expected to reach peak towrads the new year - Company should prepare to ramp up production starting August end and gradually scale up to meet the market demand.

  4. The same is expected to drastiaccly go down after the holiday season through the month of Jan - Feb - Company should have a plan to ramp down production to prevent wastage.

  5. In Q2, Q3 (Apr - Sep) wine sales is expected to be around 1500 - 2000.

  6. Q4 (Holiday Season) is expecetd to account for largest sales of about ~ 35% of yeraly volume while Q1 (Post Holiday Season) is expected to have only ~ 15% of the yearly Sales.
